decision_conditions:
Condition : 11 - Prior to commencement, including any site clearance or preparatory works, submit for approval a Construction Environment Management Plan (CEMP). This should include, but is not limed to, the following: 
A. details of the routing of construction vehicles, time of arrival and departure, and any proposed temporary traffic and pedestrian management measures during the course of construction. 
B. whilst works should take place outside of the nesting season (February - September inclusive), if works are unavoidable during this period, then a site walk over at least 48 hours prior to works 2 commencing is required by a named CIEEM accredited ecologist with experience of working in London to check for any nesting birds. In the event that a nest is found, an appropriate exclusion zone should be implemented around it until the young have fully fledged (Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended)). The law protects all wild bird species, their eggs and nests;
C. details of measures to be taken to ensure that any retained or neighbouring habitats or green spaces will not be impacted negatively by the works (including, but not limited to lighting, dust, litter, noise etc.); 
D. whilst lighting should be avoided, if lighting is necessary, details of a construction lighting plan outlining how lighting will be prevented from negatively impacting any protected and priority species during construction, in particular commuting bats and any adjacent habitats. This construction lighting plan should follow the best practice industry guidance outlined in the Bat Conservation Trust (BCT) and Institute of Lighting Professionals (ILP) Guidance Note (2023); 
E. details of measures to sensitively clear vegetation on site and to prevent any harm to wildlife; prevent the entrapment of or harm to wildlife on site, including managing excavations and construction and waste materials left on site;
